## Price Comparison: What the 25% Gap Actually Means

At identical quality specs — GIA Excellent cut, G color, VS1 clarity, 1.00ct — an oval diamond costs approximately **15–25% less** than a round brilliant.

Live data from Blue Nile for 1ct natural round brilliants shows G-VS1 Excellent at **$3,200** ([view stone →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28915027?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)). A comparable 1ct G-VS1 Excellent oval on Blue Nile typically falls in the $2,400–$2,700 range — a saving of $500–$800.

That saving is real money. Here is how to think about it:

- **If you keep the budget the same:** buy a 1ct oval instead of 1ct round and spend the $500–$800 saving on a better ring setting — a pavé band or a hidden halo that genuinely upgrades the overall appearance
- **If you use the saving on carat:** the $3,200 round budget buys a 1.20–1.30ct oval at the same quality tier — and that oval will genuinely look larger than a 1ct round

The price gap exists for two reasons: round brilliants create more waste when cut from rough crystal (about 50–55% of the rough is lost vs 40–45% for oval), and round brilliants have higher demand — roughly 50% of all engagement ring center stones are round vs about 25% oval.

The Trend Premium: oval diamond prices rose 15–20% from 2022 to 2024 driven by celebrity-driven social media demand (multiple high-profile engagements with oval rings went viral). That premium has partially stabilized in {{year}}, but ovals are no longer the bargain they were in 2020. The price gap over round has narrowed from 30–35% to 15–25%.

---

## Resale Reality: The Number That Changes Everything

If you plan to hold a diamond as an asset — even loosely — the resale market is part of the calculation.

Natural round brilliant diamonds sell on the resale market at **40–50% of original retail** in good condition with GIA certificate. This is because round brilliants are the most liquid diamond shape: every jeweler, estate dealer, and private buyer knows what they are and wants them.

Natural oval diamonds sell at **25–35% of original retail**. The market is thinner. Fancy shapes are harder to resell because buyers want to see them in person and the demand is more trend-dependent. The 2022–2024 oval premium means that buyers who paid at the top of the trend are now sitting on stones that cost them 20% more to buy than current market value.

For a $3,200 round diamond purchase: resale floor is approximately $1,280–$1,600.
For a $2,700 oval diamond purchase: resale floor is approximately $675–$945.

The oval is cheaper to buy AND cheaper to resell. These are not fully offsetting — the oval buyer genuinely gets less resale value in both absolute and percentage terms.

If resale does not matter to you — if this is purely a purchase for the joy of wearing it — then ignore this section entirely. Most engagement ring buyers should ignore it. But for buyers who think of diamonds as having any investment dimension, the round/oval resale gap is significant.

![Bar chart infographic comparing resale value as percentage of original retail for four diamond shapes — Round Brilliant 40-50 percent, Oval 25-35 percent, Princess 20-30 percent, Fancy Shapes average 15-25 percent — with dollar examples based on $3,200 round and $2,700 oval purchase prices, editorial cream and gold design with clear percentage labels](/images/round-vs-oval-diamond-resale-value-comparison-chart.avif "Round vs Oval Diamond Resale Value Comparison Chart")

